snippet.textDisplay: One thing I used to tell people all the time is you can have two of the three.... fast cheap reliable... pick 2. But you cannot have all three. No matter what it is you're going to spend anywhere from 5 to 20 grand to make it fast. the more people that are doing that type of vehicle... the cheaper it is. And the better you get at Electronics the cheaper it is. I've always done megasquirt and I'm done over a 100k miles of driving on them. other people can't even get it to start smh. One thing that is easy for some people other things are super easy for those people. I'm good at Electronics and wrenching but I can't weld. Lol probably cuz I've never had a good welder but I won't spend the money on one cuz I'm to cheap.

snippet.textDisplay: Toyota yaris is a light, maniable vehicule. Even if it has not much power, it has potential on a small technical track. As they said, the best money you can spend to cut time is obviously on tires. Even the wheels, you can put cheap used 4x100 15 inch wheels and good track tires(re71r, nt-01, rs4 or even slicks). On that I will add camber bolts for the front end to make the front a little more gripy on corners. Turboing a toyota engine that was not meant for forced induction is a big waste of money in my opinion.

A Carburetor, a set of heads, and new headers on an old american V8 would probably give you the same power boost for about a quarter of the money on a 318 V8, and suddenly I'm feeling very good about being a Muscle Car guy lol. However I still like the car, its got charm, something I cant say about all the damn exotics people keep buying on all these clickbait channels like those damn fools at daily driven exotics and the like

and hell I think its 20 grand just to change a brake disc on one of those, and even then its stuck to the worlds ugliest lambo ever made when you do. as man I miss when Lambo's were cool, and not overplayed toys for tots like they've become.

  but as they say value is subjective and I dont think it was wasted, now the problem becomes spending another 5 or 6 g to get the engine built to take the boost.

but even then I bet you probably made the money back on the video revenue, so your probably nill nill, as aint capitalism great lol as I guess the moral of the story is, if your gonna do this, do youtube videos while you do so it levels out and gets you some of your money back while you do it too lol

snippet.textDisplay: As much as I love cars there comes a point where reliability decreases and cost increases exponentially for the diminishing performance gains. There was a guy recently on a channel called LLF and he had spent about £20K ($40K AUD) to modify a Mk2 Seat Leon (Golf Gti Mk5 based car) to around 600hp. It is supercar fast in a straight line at very illegal speeds but it's massively compromised as a fast road car and you wouldn't want to daily it.

snippet.textDisplay: 6:06

On the subject of diminishing returns, you have to account for the diminishing returns of your feelings, too. For me, I've been slowly modifying my daily driver for 9 years now. The first 3 years, I left it completely stock. I was tired of it, I hated looking at it, and I wanted to trade it for something else. Then I decided to start modifying it. I couldn't afford a new car, but I had a few hundred dollars to buy some mods once in a while, so about once a year, I spend $3-400 in parts (sometimes a little more, sometimes a little less), and it feels good and rewarding to own.

On the other hand, I feel like when I've done lots of work at once and ended up completely changing a car, I don't get the same satisfaction of ownership. You end up with the same product at the end, but I feel like if I'd done everything I've done at once, I'd have probably sold it by now. New mods and parts are something I look forward to every year. I get to plan what I'm going to do next. And I haven't had a car payment in over 4 years.
